[Though the rabies situation in Cambodia, as described, is of serious concern, achieving satisfactory results within a relatively short time frame is within reach, since this country enjoys, according to the report, the fortunate situation where most dogs are owned and docile. In countries where most dogs are strays, even if their population is smaller, the prospects are significantly less promising, the timeframe longer, and costs higher.

Hopefully, the rewarding cost benefit ratio warranted by this case will help Cambodia's veterinary authorities obtain the needed financial support from donors for the vaccination and identification of the dog population as soon as possible. Public education will be the initial and essential part of the operation.

For the document "ASEAN Rabies Elimination Strategy: Ending Rabies Together by 2020," issued on 16 Sep 2015, see: https://rabiesalliance.org/media/news/asean-rabies-elimination-strategy-ending-rabies-together-by-2020. - Mod.AS

